<DOC><DOCNO> AP891221-0080 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-89 1318EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Panama-Canal     12-21 0155</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Panama-Canal,0159</SECOND><HEAD>Canal Opens Under Limited Hours</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Panama Canal reopened Thursdayafter a one-day closing caused by the U.S. invasion, the only timeanything other than natural disaster has halted operation of the75-year-old waterway.   The Panama Canal Commission said the canal will operate onlyduring the daytime until at least this weekend.   Commission spokesman Franklin Castrellon said only an average of12 ships daily will travel the waterway, compared with a normalaverage of about 33 a day when the canal operates its regularround-the-clock schedule.   The 43-mile canal had been closed since 1 a.m. Wednesday ``dueto the concern for the safety of vessels and of canal employeesduring U.S. military activities in the area,'' the commission saidin a statement from the Washington office of the canal secretary,Michael Rhode Jr.   The commission said there has been no damage to canal facilities.</TEXT></DOC>